The [Schuman Declaration](/Schuman_Declaration), occasionally referred to with a weary sigh as the [Schuman Plan](/Schuman_Declaration), was not merely a proposal; it was a rather audacious gambit. Presented on 9 May 1950 by the then-[French](/France) foreign minister, [Robert Schuman](/Robert_Schuman), it sought to place the foundational industries of [France](/France) and [West Germany](/West_Germany)—specifically the production of coal and steel—under a singular, overarching authority. This seemingly innocuous bureaucratic maneuver was, in fact, the genesis of what would later mature into the [European Coal and Steel Community](/European_Coal_and_Steel_Community), a precursor to the sprawling complex we now know as the [European Union](/European_Union). This pivotal moment is now rather enthusiastically commemorated each year as [Europe Day](/Europe_Day), coincidentally falling the day after the fifth [anniversary of the end of World War II](/Victory_in_Europe_Day) in Europe, as if to underscore its profound departure from past hostilities.

The Declaration, meticulously crafted by [Robert Schuman](/Robert_Schuman) and his indispensable advisor, [Jean Monnet](/Jean_Monnet), had a singular, albeit ambitious, purpose: to propose a framework for [European integration](/European_integration). This wasn't some abstract ideal; it was a pragmatic, almost cynical, attempt to pacify the historically volatile relationship between [France](/France) and [West Germany](/West_Germany). The strategy was brilliantly simple in its complexity: intertwine their economies so profoundly through common interests that future conflict would become not just morally reprehensible, but *materially impossible*. Schuman himself articulated this with a clarity that still echoes through the bureaucratic halls of Brussels: "In taking upon herself for more than 20 years the role of champion of a united Europe, [France](/France) has always had as her essential aim the service of peace. A united Europe was not achieved and we had war. Europe will not be made all at once, or according to a single plan. It will be built through concrete achievements which first create a de facto solidarity." He further elaborated that "The [coming together of the countries of Europe](/European_integration) requires the elimination of the [age-old opposition of France and Germany](/France%E2%80%93Germany_relations)... the solidarity in production thus established will make it plain that any war between [France](/France) and [Germany](/Germany) becomes not merely unthinkable, but materially impossible." A rather elegant way of saying, "If you share your toys, you're less likely to smash each other's faces in."

The proposal, a 1950 blueprint for European industrial integration, wasn't met with universal skepticism, surprisingly. [Konrad Adenauer](/Konrad_Adenauer), the inaugural [Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany](/Chancellor_of_Germany), extended a rather prompt and positive reception to the Declaration. His government, along with those of the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Italy](/Italy), and [Luxembourg](/Luxembourg), quickly recognized the potential. This initial acceptance laid the groundwork for the signing of the [Treaty of Paris](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1951)) on 18 April 1951 by these six founding members. This monumental agreement brought into being the [European Coal and Steel Community](/European_Coal_and_Steel_Community)—a groundbreaking supranational entity, the very first of its kind in [Europe](/Europe). It wasn't just a treaty; it was a meticulously laid stepping stone, paving the way for the subsequent establishment of the [European Economic Community](/European_Economic_Community) and, ultimately, the multifaceted entity known today as the [European Union](/European_Union). This article, for those keeping track, is part of [a series](/Category:Politics_of_the_European_Union) delving into the intricate [Politics of the European Union](/Politics_of_the_European_Union), a testament to how far a single declaration can ripple through history.

### Background

The aftermath of [World War II](/World_War_II) left [Europe](/Europe) in a state of profound exhaustion and existential dread. The continent, scarred and bifurcated by the nascent [Cold War](/Cold_War), found itself divided by the ideological chasm of the [Iron Curtain](/Iron_Curtain). The sheer, unadulterated devastation wrought by not one, but two, global conflicts—the [First](/World_War_I) and [Second](/World_War_II) World Wars—engendered a palpable, almost desperate, yearning for European cooperation. It was a sentiment born less of utopian idealism and more of grim necessity. Figures like [Winston Churchill](/Winston_Churchill), ever the orator, famously called for the formation of a "[Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe)" in his 1946 Zurich speech, envisioning a future where nations, particularly [France](/France) and [Germany](/Germany), could transcend their historical animosities. The [United States](/United_States), ever keen to stabilize the Western bloc, actively championed greater European collaboration. When the monumental [Marshall Plan](/Marshall_Plan) aid was unveiled, it came with a single, non-negotiable condition: that the substantial financial assistance be utilized by European nations in a coordinated, collaborative fashion. It wasn't just about rebuilding; it was about rebuilding *together*, a subtle nudge towards shared destiny.

This drive for cooperation was further spurred by more immediate, practical concerns. The [Monnet Plan](/Monnet_Plan), [France's](/France) ambitious post-war strategy to invigorate investment and modernize its economy, created a significant impetus for the very notion of the Schuman Plan. Pre-war, [France](/France) had been the world's largest importer of coal, and the Monnet Plan shrewdly anticipated a continued reliance on coal imports, primarily from [Germany](/Germany). However, this seemingly straightforward economic necessity was fraught with historical anxieties. In [Germany](/Germany), there was a pervasive apprehension that [France](/France) intended to secure German coal "as cheaply as possible," a move that would, predictably, bolster French steel production at Germany's expense. Conversely, within [France](/France], a lingering pre-war concern persisted: that coal resources would be made available on more favorable terms to the German market, thereby granting German industry an unfair competitive advantage.

It was against this backdrop of mutual suspicion and economic rivalry that Schuman, with Monnet's strategic foresight, sought to intervene. Their objective was not merely to regulate; it was to fundamentally transform the landscape of critical industries. Schuman aimed to dismantle the traditional cartel-like behaviors of coal and steel firms, which had historically restricted supply and manipulated national markets for their own gain. The Schuman Plan was designed to achieve something far more radical: a pooling of these vital markets and a collective expansion of production. This, they reasoned, would act as an undeniable force for peace across [Europe](/Europe). By creating a single, integrated market for the very materials of war, any conflict between [France](/France) and [Germany](/Germany) would become, quite literally, "materially impossible." It was an economic straitjacket designed for perpetual peace, a rather ingenious application of enlightened self-interest.

Schuman, a tireless advocate for European unity, had been promoting these integrative initiatives long before the Declaration itself. During his tenure as [Prime Minister of France](/Prime_Minister_of_France) (1947–48) and subsequently as [Foreign Minister](/Minister_of_Foreign_Affairs_(France)) (1948–52), he consistently championed the principles of sharing European resources within a supranational framework. He publicly articulated these convictions at the signing of the [Statute of the Council of Europe](/Statute_of_the_Council_of_Europe) in [London](/London) on 5 May 1949, setting the stage for the dramatic announcement that would follow just a year later.

### Aims and Drafting

The meticulous crafting of the [Schuman Declaration](/Schuman_Declaration) was not a solitary endeavor. [Jean Monnet](/Jean_Monnet), the quiet architect behind much of the vision, received crucial input from [Paul Reuter](/Paul_Reuter_(lawyer)), a distinguished consultant in international law to the [French](/France) foreign ministry and a respected Professor of Law at Aix-en-Provence. Further significant contributions came from [Etienne Hirsch](/%C3%89tienne_Hirsch), another key figure in French economic planning. The foundational draft documents of this historic Declaration, for those inclined to scrutinize the bureaucratic origins of grand visions, have since been made publicly available by the Jean Monnet Foundation.

The Schuman proposal, a document that would irrevocably alter the course of European history, received final approval after a critical discussion within the [French](/France) cabinet on 9 May 1950. Crucially, earlier that very day, Schuman had secured the indispensable assurance of support from [German](/Germany) Chancellor [Konrad Adenauer](/Konrad_Adenauer). This pre-emptive diplomatic maneuver was vital; without German buy-in, the entire initiative would have been stillborn.

The text of the [Schuman Declaration](/Schuman_Declaration) itself is a testament to its dual purpose: reconciliation and integration. It explicitly states, "The coming together of the nations of [Europe](/Europe) requires the elimination of the age-old opposition of [France](/France) and [Germany](/Germany)." The [French](/France) government, the Declaration asserts, "proposes that Franco-German production of coal and steel as a whole be placed under a common High Authority, within the framework of an organization open to the participation of other countries of [Europe](/Europe)." This pooling of essential resources, the very sinews of industrial power, was intended to create a shared foundation for economic development. More importantly, it was designed to "make it plain that any war between [France](/France) and [Germany](/Germany) becomes not merely unthinkable, but materially impossible." The profound significance of this proposal lay in its intention to institute a new, powerful High Authority—an entity whose decisions would be binding upon [France](/France), [Germany](/Germany), and any other participating [member countries](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union). This, the Declaration proclaimed, "will lead to the realization of the first concrete foundation of a [European federation](/European_Federation) indispensable to the preservation of peace." It was a clear, unambiguous step towards a shared sovereignty, a concept that, for all its current familiarity, was revolutionary at the time.

The Declaration, delivered with understated gravity at [Quai d'Orsay](/Quai_d%27Orsay), the venerable home of the [French Foreign Ministry](/Minister_of_Foreign_Affairs_(France)), outlined several overarching aims, each more ambitious than the last:

*   **The birth of [Europe](/Europe) as a political entity:** Moving beyond mere geographical designation to a cohesive, influential political force.
*   **To make war between [member states](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union) impossible:** A pragmatic, almost mechanical, approach to achieving perpetual peace through economic entanglement.
*   **To encourage world peace:** Recognizing that regional stability could serve as a model for broader international cooperation.
*   **To form an anti-[cartel](/Cartel) agency in the coal and steel industries of [member countries](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union):** A direct attack on monopolistic practices that had historically fueled national rivalries and economic instability.
*   **To revitalize the European economy as a whole, commencing with the coal and steel sectors:** A strategic focus on foundational industries to drive broader post-war recovery and prosperity.
*   **To offer production in coal and steel to the world without distinction or exception:** A commitment to open markets and fair trade, with the ultimate goal of elevating global living standards and fostering international development, extending even to the nascent economies of [Africa](/Africa).

These aims, while lofty, were underpinned by an acute understanding of historical grievances and economic realities, a testament to the Declaration's enduring foresight.

### Legacy

The [Schuman Declaration](/Schuman_Declaration) stands as an indelible marker, signifying the true commencement of post-[World War II](/World_War_II) Franco-German cooperation and, perhaps more importantly, the strategic re-integration of [West Germany](/West_Germany) into the broader fabric of [Western Europe](/Europe). [Konrad Adenauer](/Konrad_Adenauer), ever the pragmatist, famously declared it "our breakthrough," a concise summary of its immediate, transformative impact. The tangible manifestation of this initiative was the signing of the [Treaty of Paris](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1951)) on 18 April 1951 by the six pioneering European nations: [France](/France), [Germany](/Germany), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Italy](/Italy), [Luxembourg](/Luxembourg), and the [Netherlands](/Netherlands). This Treaty brought into existence the [European Coal and Steel Community](/European_Coal_and_Steel_Community) (ECSC), the foundational pillar among the three original European Communities, and the undisputed precursor to the vast, complex entity that is the [European Union](/European_Union) today.

The ECSC was not merely a symbolic gesture; it represented a radical departure from previous international agreements. It ushered in a common market for steel and coal across its [member countries](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union), characterized by freely determined market prices, unimpeded movement of products, and—crucially—the abolition of customs duties, taxes, subsidies, and restrictive trade practices. To ensure adherence to these new rules and to maintain transparency in pricing, it established a robust High Authority, a truly supranational body designed to transcend national interests.

Schuman, a visionary who saw beyond the immediate horizon, was a fervent advocate for even deeper European integration. He championed the concept of a [European defence community](/Treaty_establishing_the_the_European_Defence_Community), an idea that, while ultimately unratified, demonstrated the breadth of his ambition. In 1958, his enduring commitment to the European project was recognized when he became the first President of the predecessor to the modern [European Parliament](/European_Parliament). Upon his departure from office, the Parliament, in a rare moment of collective sentimentality, bestowed upon him the honorific title "Father of [Europe](/Europe)." Such is the significance of the [Schuman Declaration](/Schuman_Declaration) on 9 May 1950 that this date has been officially designated "[Europe Day](/Europe_Day)," an annual celebration of the hard-won peace and unity across the continent.

The ripple effects of this single declaration have shaped the very institutional, legal, and political landscape of [Europe](/Europe), leading to the intricate web of cooperation and governance that defines the modern [European Union](/European_Union).

### The Enduring Legacy: From Declaration to Union

The initial proposal for integrating coal and steel, born from a desire to prevent future conflicts between [France](/France) and [Germany](/Germany), blossomed into a comprehensive project of [European integration](/European_integration). This evolution is evident in the current structure of the [European Union](/European_Union), which now encompasses 27 [Member states](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union) stretching across the continent. From the initial six, the Union has grown to include nations like [Austria](/Austria), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria), [Croatia](/Croatia), [Cyprus](/Cyprus), the [Czech Republic](/Czech_Republic), [Denmark](/Denmark), [Estonia](/Estonia), [Finland](/Finland), [France](/France), [Germany](/Germany), [Greece](/Greece), [Hungary](/Hungary), [Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland), [Italy](/Italy), [Latvia](/Latvia), [Lithuania](/Lithuania), [Luxembourg](/Luxembourg), [Malta](/Malta), the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), [Poland](/Poland), [Portugal](/Portugal), [Romania](/Romania), [Slovakia](/Slovakia), [Slovenia](/Slovenia), [Spain](/Spain), and [Sweden](/Sweden). This expansion continues to be a dynamic process, with several [Candidate countries](/Potential_enlargement_of_the_European_Union) such as [Albania](/Accession_of_Albania_to_the_European_Union), [Bosnia and Herzegovina](/Accession_of_Bosnia_and_Herzegovina_to_the_European_Union), [Georgia](/Accession_of_Georgia_to_the_European_Union), [Moldova](/Accession_of_Moldova_to_the_European_Union), [Montenegro](/Accession_of_Montenegro_to_the_European_Union), [North Macedonia](/Accession_of_North_Macedonia_to_the_European_Union), [Serbia](/Accession_of_Serbia_to_the_European_Union), and [Ukraine](/Accession_of_Ukraine_to_the_European_Union) actively pursuing accession. Even countries with [suspended accession negotiations](/Potential_enlargement_of_the_European_Union), like [Turkey](/Accession_of_Turkey_to_the_European_Union), or [Applicant countries](/Potential_enlargement_of_the_European_Union) like [Kosovo](/Accession_of_Kosovo_to_the_European_Union), demonstrate the enduring gravitational pull of the European project. Nations like [Armenia](/Accession_of_Armenia_to_the_European_Union), [Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Belarus](/Belarus%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Iceland](/Iceland%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Norway](/Norway%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Russia](/Russia%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Switzerland](/Switzerland%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), and even the [United Kingdom](/Potential_re-accession_of_the_United_Kingdom_to_the_European_Union) (post-[Brexit](/Brexit)) maintain complex relationships with the Union, illustrating its pervasive influence. The unique status of [Microstates and the European Union](/Microstates_and_the_European_Union), including [Andorra](/Andorra%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Liechtenstein](/Liechtenstein%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [Monaco](/Monaco%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), [San Marino](/San_Marino%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), and [Vatican City](/Holy_See%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), further highlights the diverse forms of engagement that have emerged. The concept of "[Special territories](/Special_territories_of_states_participating_in_the_European_integration)" and the historical significance of the [EU 3 (EU founding states)](/EU_three) underscore the varied paths of this [Enlargement of the European Union](/Enlargement_of_the_European_Union), alongside the more recent phenomenon of [Withdrawal from the European Union](/Withdrawal_from_the_European_Union).

The initial [Schuman Declaration](/Schuman_Declaration) was just the first in a long line of critical [Treaties and Declarations](/Treaties_of_the_European_Union) that have shaped the Union. Following the 1950 Declaration, key milestones include the [Treaty of Paris](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1951)) (1951), the [Europe Declaration](/Europe_Declaration) (1951), the [Spaak Report](/Spaak_Report) (1956), and the foundational [Treaty of Rome](/Treaty_of_Rome) (1957), which also established the [Euratom Treaty](/Euratom_Treaty). Subsequent treaties like the [Merger Treaty](/Merger_Treaty) (1965), the [Solemn Declaration](/Solemn_Declaration_on_European_Union) (1983), the [Single European Act](/Single_European_Act) (1986), the pivotal [Maastricht Treaty](/Maastricht_Treaty) (1992) which introduced the concept of Union citizenship and laid the groundwork for the euro, the [Treaty of Amsterdam](/Treaty_of_Amsterdam) (1997), the [Treaty of Nice](/Treaty_of_Nice) (2001), the [Berlin Declaration (2007)](/Berlin_Declaration_(2007)), and the comprehensive [Treaty of Lisbon](/Treaty_of_Lisbon) (2007) have incrementally deepened integration. These treaties also delineate specific mechanisms, such as [Article 7](/Article_7_of_the_Treaty_on_European_Union) (concerning serious breaches of EU values) and [Article 50](/Withdrawal_from_the_European_Union) (governing withdrawal from the Union), and outline various [Opt-outs](/Opt-outs_in_the_European_Union) for certain member states. The journey has also included numerous [Treaties of accession](/Treaty_of_Accession_1972) in [1972](/Treaty_of_Accession_1972), [1979](/Treaty_of_Accession_1979), [1985](/Treaty_of_Accession_1985), [1994](/Treaty_of_Accession_1994), [2003](/Treaty_of_Accession_2003), [2005](/Treaty_of_Accession_2005), and [2011](/Treaty_of_Accession_2011), alongside [Treaties of withdrawal](/Withdrawal_of_Greenland_from_the_European_Communities) such as Greenland's in [1984](/Withdrawal_of_Greenland_from_the_European_Communities) and the [Brexit withdrawal agreement](/Brexit_withdrawal_agreement) in [2020](/Brexit_withdrawal_agreement). Other significant agreements, like the [Schengen Agreement](/Schengen_Agreement) (1985) and the [European Economic Area Agreement](/European_Economic_Area) (1992), have further expanded the scope of cooperation. Not all endeavors succeeded, with abandoned treaties like the proposed [European Constitution](/Treaty_establishing_a_Constitution_for_Europe) (2004) and the [UK membership renegotiation](/2015%E2%80%932016_United_Kingdom_renegotiation_of_European_Union_membership) (2015–2016) serving as reminders of the inherent challenges.

The political architecture built upon Schuman's foundation is equally complex, featuring powerful [Executive institutions](/European_Council) like the [European Council](/European_Council), currently presided over by [António Costa](/Ant%C3%B3nio_Costa) (PES), and the [European Commission](/European_Commission), led by [Ursula von der Leyen](/Ursula_von_der_Leyen) (EPP) with her [Von der Leyen Commission](/Von_der_Leyen_Commission_II) and its College of Commissioners, supported by a vast [Civil Service](/European_Civil_Service) and led by the [Secretary-General](/Secretary-General_of_the_European_Commission), [Ilze Juhansone](/Ilze_Juhansone). The [Vice Presidents](/Vice-President_of_the_European_Commission) play crucial roles in this intricate structure.

[Legislative institutions](/European_Union_legislative_procedure) are central to the Union's functioning, with the [Council of the EU](/Council_of_the_European_Union) and its rotating [Presidency](/Presidency_of_the_Council_of_the_European_Union) (e.g., [Denmark](/2025_Danish_Presidency_of_the_Council_of_the_European_Union) in July–December 2025) taking a lead role. The Council operates in various configurations, including the [GAC](/General_Affairs_Council), [FAC](/Foreign_Affairs_Council), [ECOFIN](/Economic_and_Financial_Affairs_Council), [Eurogroup](/Eurogroup), [AGRIFISH](/Agriculture_and_Fisheries_Council), [EPSCO](/Employment,_Social_Policy,_Health_and_Consumer_Affairs_Council), [COMPET](/Competitiveness_Council_(COMPET)), [TTE](/Transport,_Telecommunications_and_Energy_Council), [ENVI](/Environment_Council), [JHA](/Justice_and_Home_Affairs_Council), and [EYC](/Education,_Youth,_Culture_and_Sport_Council), each addressing specific policy areas and operating under distinct [Voting](/Voting_in_the_Council_of_the_European_Union) rules. Its [Secretariat](/General_Secretariat_of_the_Council_of_the_European_Union), led by [Secretary-General](/Secretary-General_of_the_Council_of_the_European_Union) [Thérèse Blanchet](/Th%C3%A9r%C3%A8se_Blanchet), and various [Directorates-general](/List_of_directorates-general_of_the_Council_of_the_European_Union) facilitate its work, supported by preparatory bodies like [COREPER](/Committee_of_Permanent_Representatives) and [Council Working Parties](/Council_Working_Party). The [European Parliament](/European_Parliament), comprising [Members](/List_of_members_of_the_European_Parliament_(2024%E2%80%932029)) like its current [President](/President_of_the_European_Parliament) [Roberta Metsola](/Roberta_Metsola), represents the citizens. Its [largest groups](/Political_groups_of_the_European_Parliament), such as the [EPP](/European_People%27s_Party_group) led by [Manfred Weber](/Manfred_Weber) and the [S&D](/Progressive_Alliance_of_Socialists_and_Democrats) led by [Iratxe García](/Iratxe_Garc%C3%ADa), play pivotal roles in the [10th session](/Tenth_European_Parliament) (2024–2029). The [Bureau](/Bureau_of_the_European_Parliament), [Vice Presidents](/Vice-President_of_the_European_Parliament), [Quaestor](/Quaestor_(European_Parliament)), and [Conference](/Conference_of_Presidents_of_the_European_Parliament) oversee its operations. The involvement of [National parliaments](/National_parliaments_of_the_European_Union) further underscores the democratic legitimacy of the legislative process.

The [Judicial institutions](/Court_of_Justice_of_the_European_Union), primarily the [Court of Justice of the European Union](/Court_of_Justice_of_the_European_Union), ensure the rule of [European Union law](/European_Union_law). This includes the [European Court of Justice](/European_Court_of_Justice) with its [Members](/List_of_members_of_the_European_Court_of_Justice) and [Advocates General](/Advocate_General_(European_Union)), whose [Rulings](/List_of_European_Court_of_Justice_rulings) shape jurisprudence, and the [General Court](/General_Court_(European_Union)). [Auditory institutions](/European_Court_of_Auditors), such as the [European Court of Auditors](/European_Court_of_Auditors), provide crucial oversight, complemented by the [Internal Audit Service of the Commission](/Internal_Audit_Service_(European_Commission)), the [Committee on Budgetary Control of the Parliament](/European_Parliament_Committee_on_Budgetary_Control), and the [Economic and Financial Affairs configuration of the Council](/Economic_and_Financial_Affairs_Council). The [European Anti-Fraud Office](/European_Anti-Fraud_Office) (OLAF) and the [European Public Prosecutor's Office](/European_Public_Prosecutor%27s_Office) (EPPO) tackle financial misconduct.

The [European Central Bank](/European_Central_Bank), under [President](/President_of_the_European_Central_Bank) [Christine Lagarde](/Christine_Lagarde), is a cornerstone of the [Economic and Monetary Union of the European Union](/Economic_and_Monetary_Union_of_the_European_Union) (EMU) and the broader [European System of Central Banks](/European_System_of_Central_Banks) (ESCB), managing the [Euro banknotes](/Euro_banknotes) and [Euro coins](/Euro_coins) that are the physical embodiment of a shared currency.

Beyond these core institutions, numerous [Other bodies](/European_Investment_Bank) contribute to the EU's functioning. The European Investment Bank Group includes the [European Investment Bank](/European_Investment_Bank) and the [European Investment Fund](/European_Investment_Fund). The [European Stability Mechanism](/European_Stability_Mechanism) provides financial assistance, while the [European University Institute](/European_University_Institute) fosters academic excellence. The [Unified Patent Court](/Unified_Patent_Court) harmonizes patent litigation. A multitude of [Agencies, decentralised independent bodies and joint undertakings](/Agencies,_decentralised_independent_bodies_and_joint_undertakings_of_the_European_Union_and_the_Euratom) exist, ranging from single market agencies to [European Supervisory Authorities](/European_Supervisory_Authorities) (ESFS), executive agencies, and Euratom agencies. Notable examples include the [European Institute of Innovation and Technology](/European_Institute_of_Innovation_and_Technology) and the [European Data Protection Board](/European_Data_Protection_Board). Independent bodies like the [European Data Protection Supervisor](/European_Data_Protection_Supervisor) and the [European Ombudsman](/European_Ombudsman) ensure accountability. [Advisory bodies](/Advisory_bodies_to_the_European_Union) such as the [European Committee of the Regions](/European_Committee_of_the_Regions) and the [European Economic and Social Committee](/European_Economic_and_Social_Committee) provide crucial input, alongside the [Political and Security Committee](/Political_and_Security_Committee) and the [European Union Military Committee](/European_Union_Military_Committee). Inter-institutional bodies like the [Publications Office of the European Union](/Publications_Office_of_the_European_Union) and the [European External Action Service](/European_External_Action_Service) facilitate coordination.

The [European Atomic Energy Community](/European_Atomic_Energy_Community) ([Euratom](/European_Atomic_Energy_Community)), established alongside the EEC, continues to play a vital role in coordinating [nuclear power in the European Union](/Nuclear_power_in_the_European_Union) among its 27 [member states](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union), and even maintains cooperation with associated states like [Switzerland](/Switzerland) and the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom).

The [Economic and Monetary Union](/Economic_and_Monetary_Union_of_the_European_Union) (EMU) has seen the [euro](/Euro) adopted by the 20 [Eurozone members](/Eurozone), including [Austria](/Austria), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Croatia](/Croatia), [Cyprus](/Cyprus), [Estonia](/Estonia), [Finland](/Finland), [France](/France), [Germany](/Germany), [Greece](/Greece), [Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland), [Italy](/Italy), [Latvia](/Latvia), [Lithuania](/Lithuania), [Luxembourg](/Luxembourg), [Malta](/Malta), the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), [Portugal](/Portugal), [Slovakia](/Slovakia), [Slovenia](/Slovenia), and [Spain](/Spain). The [Eurogroup](/Eurogroup), currently led by [Paschal Donohoe](/Paschal_Donohoe), coordinates policies among these nations. Other [Currencies of the European Union](/Currencies_of_the_European_Union), such as the [Bulgarian lev](/Bulgarian_lev), [Czech koruna](/Czech_koruna), [Danish krone](/Danish_krone) (with its [euro](/Euro) opt-out), [Hungarian forint](/Hungarian_forint), [Polish złoty](/Polish_z%C5%82oty), [Romanian leu](/Romanian_leu), and [Swedish krona](/Swedish_krona), exist alongside the euro, with countries like [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria_and_the_euro) and [Romania](/Romania_and_the_euro) participating in [ERM II](/European_Exchange_Rate_Mechanism) as they work towards [Enlargement of the eurozone](/Enlargement_of_the_eurozone).

The [Schengen Area](/Schengen_Area), a direct consequence of the drive for free movement, now includes 27 [EU member states](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union) like [Austria](/Austria), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria), [Croatia](/Croatia), the [Czech Republic](/Czech_Republic), [Denmark](/Denmark), [Estonia](/Estonia), [Finland](/Finland), [France](/France), [Germany](/Germany), [Greece](/Greece), [Hungary](/Hungary), [Italy](/Italy), [Latvia](/Latvia), [Lithuania](/Lithuania), [Luxembourg](/Luxembourg), [Malta](/Malta), the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), [Poland](/Poland), [Portugal](/Portugal), [Romania](/Romania), [Slovakia](/Slovakia), [Slovenia](/Slovenia), [Spain](/Spain), and [Sweden](/Sweden), alongside non-EU members such as [Iceland](/Iceland), [Liechtenstein](/Liechtenstein), and [Norway](/Norway). [Cyprus](/Cyprus) and [Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland) (with its opt-out) remain outside the Schengen Area. Mechanisms like [ETIAS](/European_Travel_Information_and_Authorisation_System), the [Prüm Convention](/Pr%C3%BCm_Convention), and the [Schengen Information System](/Schengen_Information_System) underpin this borderless zone, along with its [Visa Information System](/Visa_Information_System) and comprehensive [Visa policy of the Schengen Area](/Visa_policy_of_the_Schengen_Area).

The [European Economic Area](/European_Economic_Area) (EEA) extends many of the EU's single market benefits to non-EU members [Iceland](/Iceland), [Liechtenstein](/Liechtenstein), and [Norway](/Norway), alongside the 27 EU [member states](/Member_state_of_the_European_Union). The [EEA Joint Committee](/EEA_Joint_Committee) and the recognition of [EEA National Identity cards](/National_identity_cards_in_the_European_Economic_Area) are integral to its functioning.

Democratic participation is facilitated through [Elections to the European Parliament](/Elections_to_the_European_Parliament), where [European parties](/European_political_party) and [European foundations](/European_political_foundation) compete within [Political groups of the European Parliament](/Political_groups_of_the_European_Parliament). The concept of a [Spitzenkandidat](/Spitzenkandidat) has emerged, and elections are organized by [Constituencies](/European_Parliament_constituency) with specific [Apportionment](/Apportionment_in_the_European_Parliament). Numerous [Referendums related to the EU](/Referendums_related_to_the_European_Union) have also shaped its trajectory, with elections occurring every five years, from [1979](/1979_European_Parliament_election) to the [latest election in 2024](/2024_European_Parliament_election).

The Union operates under a unique system of [European Union law](/European_Union_law), built upon the [Acquis](/Acquis_communautaire). Key principles include [Conferral](/Principle_of_conferral), [Primacy](/Primacy_of_European_Union_law) (as established in [ECJ Case 6/64](/Costa_v_ENEL)), and [Subsidiarity](/Subsidiarity_(European_Union)). Legal instruments include [Regulation](/Regulation_(European_Union)), [Directive](/Directive_(European_Union)), and [Decision](/Decision_(European_Union)), alongside non-binding [Recommendation](/Recommendation_(European_Union)). The concept of [Democratic legitimacy](/Democratic_legitimacy_of_the_European_Union) is paramount, and the [Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union](/Charter_of_Fundamental_Rights_of_the_European_Union) enshrines core human rights.

The EU's wide-ranging [Policies and issues](/Budget_of_the_European_Union) include a shared [Budget](/Budget_of_the_European_Union), a [Customs Union](/European_Union_Customs_Union), numerous [Free Trade Agreements](/European_Union_free_trade_agreements), and the expansive [European Single Market](/European_Single_Market). The [Area of freedom, security and justice](/Area_of_freedom,_security_and_justice) is a key policy domain. Sectoral policies include the [Common Agricultural Policy](/Common_Agricultural_Policy), [Energy policy of the European Union](/Energy_policy_of_the_European_Union), [Common Fisheries Policy](/Common_Fisheries_Policy), and [Regional policy of the European Union](/Regional_policy_of_the_European_Union). The Union also fosters a sense of [Citizenship of the European Union](/Citizenship_of_the_European_Union), reflected in common [Passports of the European Union](/Passports_of_the_European_Union) and a burgeoning [Pan-European identity](/Pan-European_identity), though this is often contested by [Euroscepticism](/Euroscepticism) despite efforts towards [Pro-Europeanism](/Pro-Europeanism). Financial stability is underpinned by the [European banking union](/European_banking_union), [European Banking Supervision](/European_Banking_Supervision), and the [Single Resolution Mechanism](/Single_Resolution_Mechanism), alongside the [Capital Markets Union](/Capital_Markets_Union) and the [European System of Financial Supervision](/European_System_of_Financial_Supervision). Debates continue on the [Institutional seats of the European Union](/Institutional_seats_of_the_European_Union), the nature of [European integration](/European_integration) (be it [Supranationalism](/Supranational_union) or a [European Federation](/European_Federation)), and concepts like a [Multi-speed Europe](/Multi-speed_Europe) and [Enhanced cooperation](/Enhanced_cooperation).

In the realm of [Foreign relations](/Foreign_relations_of_the_European_Union), the [High Representative](/High_Representative_of_the_Union_for_Foreign_Affairs_and_Security_Policy), currently [Kaja Kallas](/Kaja_Kallas), leads the [European External Action Service](/European_External_Action_Service) (EEAS) in implementing the [Common Foreign and Security Policy](/Common_Foreign_and_Security_Policy) (CFSP) and the [Common Security and Defence Policy](/Common_Security_and_Defence_Policy) (CSDP). The EU maintains relations with a vast array of global partners, from [Argentina](/Argentina%E2%80%93European_Union_relations) to the [United States](/United_States%E2%80%93European_Union_relations), and actively participates in multilateral forums like the [G7](/Group_of_Seven) and [G20](/G20). The [European Union–NATO relations](/European_Union%E2%80%93NATO_relations) are particularly significant. The historical context of the [United Kingdom membership of the European Union](/United_Kingdom_membership_of_the_European_Union) and [Post-Brexit United Kingdom relations with the European Union](/Post-Brexit_United_Kingdom_relations_with_the_European_Union) highlights the complexities of these ties. The [Common Travel Area](/Common_Travel_Area) with [Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland) is another unique arrangement. The EU's engagement with the [United Nations](/European_Union_and_the_United_Nations), its [Association Agreements](/European_Union_Association_Agreement), the [European Neighbourhood Policy](/European_Neighbourhood_Policy), and initiatives like the [Eastern Partnership](/Eastern_Partnership) and [Euronest Parliamentary Assembly](/Euronest_Parliamentary_Assembly) demonstrate its global reach and diplomatic efforts.

Over the decades, some bodies have become [Defunct](/European_Communities), such as the original [European Communities](/European_Communities) (1958–1993), including the [European Coal and Steel Community](/European_Coal_and_Steel_Community) itself and the [European Economic Community](/European_Economic_Community), which later became the [European Community](/European_Community). The [Western European Union](/Western_European_Union) and the [Convention on the Future of Europe](/Convention_on_the_Future_of_Europe) also represent past iterations or attempts at integration.

The history of this ambitious undertaking, from [Pre-1948 ideas](/Ideas_of_European_unity_before_1948) through distinct periods like [1948–1957](/History_of_the_European_integration_(1948%E2%80%931957)), [1958–1972](/History_of_the_European_Communities_(1958%E2%80%931972)), [1973–1993](/History_of_the_European_Communities_(1973%E2%80%931993)), [1993–2004](/History_of_the_European_Union_(1993%E2%80%932004)), and [2004–present](/History_of_the_European_Union_since_2004), is meticulously documented in the [Timeline of European Union history](/Timeline_of_European_Union_history). This narrative includes the evolution of key [Commissions](/European_Commission), from the [Hallstein Commission](/Hallstein_Commission) (1958) to the current [Von der Leyen Commission II](/Von_der_Leyen_Commission_II) (2024), and the pivotal role of [Founding fathers of the European Union](/Founding_fathers_of_the_European_Union).

The Schuman Declaration, a seemingly simple proposal for industrial integration, thus stands as the bedrock upon which this elaborate edifice of international cooperation has been meticulously, and sometimes painfully, constructed. It is a testament to the enduring, if often frustrating, human desire to transcend conflict through shared interests—or, perhaps, to simply make war too inconvenient to pursue.

